one of my favorite verses. how often do we get so caught up in checklists and to-do’s and events and calendar invites and accomplishments and plans? these are great things, however, I don’t know about you, but I have to be careful to not allow them to become THE thing. we are made for more. we are made for relationship with Christ. anything else is a shadow love and the false fulfillment found in them will fade. 

when I think about the moments I feel the most at rest, it‘s over my morning coffee with the Lord, it‘s during a slow drive down a country road listening to worship music, it’s on a walk by the lake admiring the work of His hand, or journaling near the candlelight the Words He’s whispered to me. 

the mundane, the quiet, the simple, those moments with the Lord are the ones that are the utmost peaceable. Intentional quiet. Intentionally slowing down in a world that says to run faster.

Peace and rebellion cannot coexist. If Jesus is not your Lord and Savior, peace will be just out of reach, no matter how wonderful your circumstances may seem. But to those who are children of The King, peace will remain even in the deepest of sorrows — even then, there will still be a soul deep joyful song to sing. 

“And then You silenced my fears and I stood up to dance. They were all so confused given my circumstance. I knew I couldn't explain it.”

& beauty will be seen everywhere. For God, The Good Father, reveals extraordinary moments in the mundane to those who’ll just posture their heart as—Lord, give me eyes to see what You do. Give me ears to hear what You’d have me hear. Give me the chance to serve and then give me the courage to when those chances appear. Lord, give me deeper gratitude. 

“Now if God so clothes the grass of the field, which today is, and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, will He not much more clothe you, O you of little faith?” Matthew 6.

“I think you do know what you want. Maybe it just feels lost in the loudness of other people’s opinions. We compare how we’re living to the millions of ways people are online, and we feel we should be doing something different. “I should go back to school,” “I should travel,” “I should be farther along in my career,” “I should slow down”—be wary of these ‘shoulds.’ A lot of times, they’re a sign the idea didn’t come from you.

You know what you want. You may feel scared or not ready, but you know. What you want feels steady, quiet, and sure. It’s the thing you’re consistently curious about, something that keeps gently tugging at you, waiting for you to notice it. Sometimes you just need to create some quiet space amidst the loudness to hear yourself again.”

have been feeling exceptionally grateful lately—a gift from God, undoubtedly. on my own, I have a tendency to fret & overthink & over-plan, about things & places & people that I have no business allowing to hold so much space in my mind! even beautiful things, I’ve noticed, tend to lock me into a future-focused headspace where I plan and organize and mood board. and even beautiful things, I’ve noticed, have filled my mind more than the present splendors of life. and I am sure I’ve missed many of God’s whispers and winks and love-notes by focusing more on the future than the present.

but lately I haven’t been. lately I’ve had such gratitude and it’s made me feel so present. present in this season of engagement. present in my home and at my job and in traffic. with old friends and new ones. on big hikes and short walks. In kitchen conversations and instrumental soundtracks on long drives. A gift from God, undoubtedly. Praying for a deeper heart posture of presence. 

“Today is mine. Tomorrow is none of my business. If I peer anxiously into the fog of the future, I will strain my spiritual eyes so that I will not see clearly what is required of me now.” —Elisabeth Elliot

What does it mean to be meek?

The Greek word is Práos. Or: gentleness. It means ‘strength under control.’ The supernatural ability, in The Spirits power, not to demand control or be extreme in our responses. 

It is how we choose to accept God’s will, different than ours it may seem at times, and how we choose to respond to man’s treatment of us. Of going through all things with grace, trusting that all really will be well in the end, just as God has said. 

“Meekness is not indecision or laziness or feminine fragility or loose sentimentalism or indifference or affable neutrality. Meekness is most emphatically not weakness. Do you remember who was the meekest man in the Old Testament? Moses! (Numbers 12:3). My mental image of him is not of a feeble man. It is shaped by Michelangelo’s sculpture and painting and by the biblical descriptions.” - E.E. 

You can’t be described as meek without strength. Remember, ‘strength under control.’ Oh, how a picture of God that is. Christ Jesus, fully man and fully God, allowed Himself to be nailed to a tree He created when He could have, at any moment, called on a legion of angels. (Matthew 26:53) All for love. All for us. To die for our sins and save us. The ability to exhibit strength, but to choose gentleness. This is meekness. I’m in awe of the humility of God. 

“Meekness is teachability. “The meek will He teach his way” (Psalm 25:9). It is the readiness to be shown, which includes the readiness to lay down my fixed notions, my objections and “what ifs” or “but what abouts,” my certainties about the rightness of what I have always done or thought or said. It is the child’s glad “Show me! Is this the way? Please help me.” We won’t make it into the kingdom without that childlikeness, that simple willingness to be taught and corrected and helped. “Receive with meekness the engrafted word, which is able to save your souls” (James 1:21). Meekness is an explicitly spiritual quality, a fruit of the Spirit.” — E.E. Through it we will inherit the earth (Matthew 5).
